["name" =>"50 groundbreaking startup ideas", "categories"=>"Videos", "representation"=>"by Tim Finnigan.", "description"=>"50 startup founders discussing the origins of their ideas.", "content"=>"This is an awesome video compilation of 50 different startup founders discussing the origins of their ideas. This video features founders like Brian Chesky of AirBnB, Kevin Systrom of Instagram, Jack Dorsey of Twitter, Ryan Hoover of Product Hunt and David Karp of Tumblr.<br />WATCH THE VIDEO", "url"=>"watch the video", "logo"=>"http://startupstash.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/01/43.4groundbreakingStartupIdeas_a-150x150.png"],
["name" =>"Growth Hacker TV", "categories"=>"Videos", "representation"=>"by Bronson Taylor.", "description"=>"Trying to grow a startup? Hustlers don't watch cable, they watch Growth Hacker TV. New episodes released weekly.", "content"=>"Are you an entrepreneur who is trying to grow a startup? Growth Hacker TV has over 100 episodes where experts reveal their secrets. Growth Hacker TV is an educational resource for founders and entrepreneurs that are trying to grow a startup. Building a product is the easy part, getting people to care and pay attention is not. <br />There are very few people in the world that really understand how startups grow. Have you grown a product to millions of users? Yeah, me neither. Luckily, the people that come on Growth Hacker TV have.<br />GROWTHHACKER.TV", "url"=>"growthhacker.tv", "facebook"=>"https://www.facebook.com/growthhackertv", "twitter"=>"https://twitter.com/growthhackertv", "logo"=>"http://startupstash.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/01/43.5growthhackertv_a-150x150.png"],
["name" =>"Sandwich Video", "categories"=>"Videos", "representation"=>"Awesome startup videos.", "description"=>"Sandwich Video makes videos, mostly for neat tech products.", "content"=>"In 2009, Adam Lisagor made what became the first of his many videos for neat tech products. He’d co-developed an iOS app with a friend, made a video to promote it, and became his own first client. A year later, with enough paying customers to make it a real thing, he incorporated as Sandwich Video Inc. <br />Their website is not made to sell—they want to share through the medium of video. People usually watch because they’ve come to learn, and they like to help make that happen. Check out their awesome videos on the site.<br />SANDWICHVIDEO.COM", "url"=>"sandwichvideo.com", "twitter"=>"https://twitter.com/sandwich", "logo"=>"http://startupstash.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/01/43.6sandwichvideo_a-150x150.png"],
["name" =>"#StartupMovies", "categories"=>"Videos", "representation"=>"Movies/Series/Documentaries on Startups and Entrepreneurs.", "description"=>"#StartupMovies offers the best movies, series and geeks documentaries featuring startups and entrepreneurs.", "content"=>"Sign up for their newsletter and get one recommendation every week on the best movies, series or documentary featuring startups and entrepreneur life stories. <br />#StartupMovies was made by BeGenius, they help Entrepreneurs and Startups Bring Awesome Products and Services to Markets.<br />#STARTUPMOVIES", "url"=>"#startupmovies", "facebook"=>"https://www.facebook.com/BeGeniusLLC", "twitter"=>"https://twitter.com/BeGeniusLLC", "logo"=>"http://startupstash.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/01/43.7startupmovies_a-150x150.png"],
["name" =>"Small Empires", "categories"=>"Videos", "representation"=>"with Alexis Ohanian.", "description"=>"Small Empires is The Verge’s weekly show on rising startups.", "content"=>"Small Empires with Alexis Ohanian is The Verge’s weekly show that visits rising startups and provides never-before-seen access to the men and women building our future. Back in 2005 Alexis Ohanian was a founder of Reddit — which modestly calls itself “the front page of the internet” — and he went on to launch companies like Breadpig and The Hipmunk. Be sure to check back every week for a new episode diving into the fast-paced startup scene.<br />SMALL EMPIRES", "url"=>"small empires", "facebook"=>"https://www.facebook.com/verge", "twitter"=>"https://twitter.com/verge", "logo"=>"http://startupstash.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/01/43.8smallempires_a-150x150.png"],
["name" =>"The #AskGaryVee Show", "categories"=>"Videos", "representation"=>"by Gary Vaynerchuk.", "description"=>"You ask questions, Gary Vaynerchuck will try to answer them.", "content"=>"In the #AskGaryVee show, the awesome Gary Vaynerchuck answers your questions about marketing, social media, and entrepreneurship. Want to get on the show? Tweet Gary your question with #AskGaryVee!<br />#ASKGARYVEE YOUTUBE", "url"=>"#askgaryvee youtube", "facebook"=>"https://www.facebook.com/gary", "twitter"=>"https://twitter.com/garyvee", "logo"=>"http://startupstash.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/01/43.9AskGaryVee_a-150x150.jpg"],
["name" =>"Startup Grind Videos", "categories"=>"Videos", "representation"=>"Educate, inspire, connect. Helping startups be successful.", "description"=>"Startup Grind is a global startup community designed to educate, inspire, and connect entrepreneurs.", "content"=>"They’ve interviewed some of the best entrepreneurs, investors and authors on the Startup Grind stage. This page show their favorite videos (for the full list of Startup Grind interviews, visit their YouTube channel). <br />Startup Grind Videos", "url"=>"startup grind videos", "facebook"=>"https://www.facebook.com/StartupGrind", "twitter"=>"https://twitter.com/startupgrind", "logo"=>"http://startupstash.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/01/43.10startupgrind_a-150x150.png"],
["name" =>"Paul Graham’s Essays", "categories"=>"Articles", "representation"=>"by Paul Graham.", "description"=>"Paul Graham is a programmer, writer, and investor.", "content"=>"Paul Graham is a programmer, writer, and investor. In 1995, he and Robert Morris started Viaweb, the first software as a service company. Viaweb was acquired by Yahoo in 1998, where it became Yahoo Store. In 2001 Grahams started publishing essays on website paulgraham.com, which in 2014 got 12 million page views. <br />In 2005 he and Jessica Livingston, Robert Morris, and Trevor Blackwell started Y Combinator, the first of a new type of startup incubator. Since 2005 Y Combinator has funded over 800 startups, including Dropbox, Airbnb, Stripe, and Reddit. Some of Paul’s best essays are: “How to Make Wealth”, “How to Start a Startup”, “Hiring is Obsolete”, “The Hardest Lesson for Startups to Learn”, “The 18 Mistakes that Kill Startups”, and “Why To Not Not Start a Startup”.<br />PAULGRAHAM.COM", "url"=>"paulgraham.com", "twitter"=>"https://twitter.com/paulg", "logo"=>"http://startupstash.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/01/44.1paulgraham_a-150x150.png"],
["name" =>"How to write emails like a CEO", "categories"=>"Articles", "representation"=>"by Andrew Torba.", "description"=>"Andrew Torba is the Co-Founder and CEO of @Kuhcoon.", "content"=>"“There are many things CEOs care about, but arguably one of the most important things is their time. Whether they are running a Fortune 500 company or a startup company, CEOs have a lot on their plate and in a global economy every second counts. When I first entered the startup world I wrote novel-like emails to my team members. This ended in long drawn out email chains that took up a great majority of my time as well as my team’s. I quickly learned to “filter out the fluff” and focus on the one or two key points I was trying to make.”<br />READ ARTICLE", "url"=>"read article", "twitter"=>"https://twitter.com/torbahax", "logo"=>"http://startupstash.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/01/44.2howtowriteemails_a-150x150.png"],
["name" =>"The spark file", "categories"=>"Articles", "representation"=>"by Steven Johnson.", "description"=>"Steven Johnson is a writer and has published 9 books.", "content"=>"“For the past eight years or so I’ve been maintaining a single document where I keep all my hunches: ideas for articles, speeches, software features, startups, ways of framing a chapter I know I’m going to write, even whole books. <br />I now keep it as a Google document so I can update it from wherever I happen to be. There’s no organizing principle to it, no taxonomy–just a chronological list of semi-random ideas that I’ve managed to capture before I forgot them. I call it the spark file.”<br />READ ARTICLE", "url"=>"read article", "twitter"=>"https://twitter.com/stevenbjohnson", "logo"=>"http://startupstash.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/01/44.3thesparkfile_a-150x150.png"],
["name" =>"You are not late", "categories"=>"Articles", "representation"=>"by Kevin Kelly.", "description"=>"Kevin Kelly is a Senior Maverick at Wired, Cool Tools maven, author of What Technology Wants, True Films, and 1,000 True Fans.", "content"=>"“In terms of the internet, nothing has happened yet. The internet is still at the beginning of its beginning. If we could climb into a time machine and journey 30 years into the future, and from that vantage look back to today, we’d realize that most of the greatest products running the lives of citizens in 2044 were not invented until after 2014.”<br />READ ARTICLE", "url"=>"read article", "twitter"=>"https://twitter.com/kevin2kelly", "logo"=>"http://startupstash.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/01/44.4youarenotlate_a-150x150.png"],
["name" =>"Good and bad reasons to become an entrepreneur", "categories"=>"Articles", "representation"=>"by Dustin Moskvitz.", "description"=>"Dustin Moskovitz is a co-founder of Facebook, and now founder at Asana.", "content"=>"“Recently we hosted a Q&A at Asana that I participated in with Ben Horowitz, Matt Cohler, and Justin Rosenstein. Marcus Wohlsen from Wired attended and wrote an article that discussed our views on the culture of entrepreneurship in Silicon Valley. This is an important topic, so I want to take some time to clarify what we meant in this blog post. Before I do, I’d like to emphasize that we were talking exclusively about Silicon Valley culture and not the more general ‘small business entrepreneur.’ So for our audience at the time, entrepreneur meant Silicon Valley startup technology entrepreneur.”<br />READ ARTICLE", "url"=>"read article", "twitter"=>"https://twitter.com/moskov", "logo"=>"http://startupstash.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/01/44.5goodandbadreasons_a-150x150.png"],
["name" =>"Quitting my corporate job", "categories"=>"Articles", "representation"=>"by Ali Mese.", "description"=>"Ali Mese is a Storyteller, Entrepreneur & Freelancer.", "content"=>"“Every time I met with those friends, I didn’t have many updates to give them in response to their repeated questions, such as, “So, how is your startup going? You are going to be the next Zuckerberg, right?” <br />“Oh man, we are so proud of you and we are so sure you will soon receive a huge round of investment.”<br />Doing a startup was a long journey and I was putting myself under so much pressure by giving such a f*ck about what other people think.”<br />READ ARTICLE", "url"=>"read article", "facebook"=>"https://www.facebook.com/alimeseu", "twitter"=>"https://twitter.com/meseali", "logo"=>"http://startupstash.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/01/44.6quittingmycorporatejob_a-150x150.png"],
["name" =>"The artifacts of Product Hunt", "categories"=>"Articles", "representation"=>"by Ryan Hoover.", "description"=>"The Product Hunt story told in tweets, photos, and emails.", "content"=>"After announcing their $6.1M in Series A funding, led by Andreessen Horowitz, Hoover wanted to tell a bit more of the Product Hunt story as he experienced it in tweets, photos and emails.<br />READ ARTICLE", "url"=>"read article", "twitter"=>"http://twitter.com/rrhoover", "logo"=>"http://startupstash.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/01/44.7artifactsofproducthunt_a-150x150.png"],
["name" =>"Postmortem of a VC-backed Startup", "categories"=>"Articles", "representation"=>"by Brett Martin.", "description"=>"Lessons Learned from the rise and fall of @Sonar.", "content"=>"“For those unfamiliar, Sonar Media Inc. was a mobile app created to help make the world a friendlier place. Our mobile app buzzed in your pocket when friends were near and ushered in a new wave of “Ambient Social Networking” companies. <br />Downloaded by millions of people all over the world, Sonar was promoted by Apple and Google in 100+ countries, won numerous awards such as runner-up at TechCrunch Disrupt and Ad:Tech Best Mobile Startup, raised nearly $2,000,000 from prominent angels and VCs, and was featured on more than 300 publications including the New York Times, CNN, CNBC, TechCrunch, and TIME.<br />And yet, we failed.”<br />READ ARTICLE", "url"=>"read article", "twitter"=>"https://twitter.com/brett1211", "logo"=>"http://startupstash.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/01/44.8postmortem_a-150x150.png"],
["name" =>"Writing a business plan", "categories"=>"Articles", "representation"=>"by Sequoia Capital.", "description"=>"Sequoia helps founders turn imaginative ideas into enduring companies.", "content"=>"At Sequoia they like business plans that present a lot of information in as few words as possible. The following business plan format, within 15–20 slides, is all that’s needed…<br />SEQUOIACAP.COM/GROVE", "url"=>"sequoiacap.com/grove", "facebook"=>"https://www.facebook.com/SequoiaCap", "twitter"=>"https://twitter.com/sequoia", "logo"=>"http://startupstash.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/01/44.9sequoia_a-150x150.jpeg"],
["name" =>"What I wish I knew before I pitched Linkedin to VCs", "categories"=>"Articles", "representation"=>"by Reid Hoffman.", "description"=>"Reid Hoffman is an Entrepreneur, Product Strategist and Investor.", "content"=>"“Entrepreneurs often ask me for help with their financing decks. Because we value integrity and confidentiality at Greylock, we never share an entrepreneur’s pitch deck with others. What I’ve honorably been able to do, however, is share the deck I used to pitch LinkedIn to Greylock for a Series B investment back in 2004.<br />This past May was the 10th anniversary of LinkedIn, and while reflecting on my entrepreneurial journey, I realized that no one gets to see the presentation decks for successful companies. This gave me an idea: I could help many more entrepreneurs by making the deck available not just to the Greylock network of entrepreneurs, but to everyone.”<br />READ THE ARTICLE", "url"=>"read the article", "twitter"=>"https://twitter.com/reidhoffman", "logo"=>"http://startupstash.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/01/44.10whatiwishiknew_a-150x150.png"],
